Thank you for all of the responses.

Mike,

I&#39;m curious as to why the plastic enclosure.  I know on your video 
you mentioned both a shoebox or cigar box could be used as well.

I&#39;m going to try this chamber experiment, but my question is what 
enclosure would be best so as not to inhibit the sounds, by the 
material of the enclosure actually absorbing any of the sound.

I&#39;m no scientist by any means, so maybe my concern is mute, but it 
would seem to me that perhaps a glass (or lead crystal) or metal (tin 
box) enclosure would be an interesting experiment as well.

Also, have you given any thought to a single toggle/power up switch 
that would power all devices on at once, perhaps from outside of the 
box, thereby eliminating the need to open and close the box with each 
session.

What do you think?

thanks!


--- In EVP-ITC@yahoogroups.com, &quot;M.A. Coletta (Mike)&quot; 
&lt;michaelcoletta@...&gt; wrote:
&gt;
&gt; Hi Rita,
&gt; 
&gt; Welcome to the group.  Yes, Bruce is correct... my sound chamber 
design is an experiment to see how well that design works.  I took 
the basic components of a typical ghost box system and placed them 
into the plastic enclosure. But to hear what is desired does not 
always require a chamber. The chamber is just a place where the three 
sound components can mix and be captured by the microphone.
&gt; Just one of many different methods that can be used.
&gt; 
&gt; I have even got good results by just using a 12-470 and a recorder 
in the open air.
&gt; 
&gt; I did build a couple of new chamber systems and will probably build 
one more for a total of 4.  And I&#39;ll probably provide some of those 
to some locals here to test. I&#39;d like to get others input on this 
experimental design. LC is also putting one together using the 12-
469. So we will have data from that area too.
&gt; 
&gt; Again... welcome to the group.
